        "max": 100,
        "value": 20,
        "unit": "W",
        "description": "Typical range for pulsed laser cleaning of delicate metals like gold to avoid melting (mp 1064°C); start low due to high reflectivity at 532 nm. Recommended starting at 20 W for contamination removal. Max safe ~100 W with fast scanning to prevent substrate damage. Source: Studies on laser cleaning of gold artifacts (e.g., J. Cult. Herit. 2018, DOI:10.1016/j.culher.2018.03.005); manufacturer specs from IPG Photonics for 532 nm systems."
      },
      "scan_speed": {
        "min": 10,
        "max": 5000,
        "unit": "mm/s",
        "value": 500,
        "description": "Range for effective cleaning without excessive heat buildup; slower for heavy contamination (100-500 mm/s), faster for light (1000-2000 mm/s). Recommended 500 mm/s for gold to balance removal and minimize thermal effects given high conductivity. Source: Industry standards from Laser Institute of America guidelines and equipment manuals (e.g., Coherent Inc. scanning systems)."
      },
      "pulse_width": {
        "min": 0.1,
        "max": 1000,
        "unit": "ns",
        "value": 10,
        "description": "Nanosecond regime (5-50 ns) typical for industrial cleaning of gold; picosecond (ps) or femtosecond (fs) for ultra-minimal HAZ but costlier. Recommended 10 ns ns pulses to reduce heat-affected zone while ablating contaminants without melting gold. Source: Laser physics research on metal ablation (e.g., Appl. Phys. A 2015, DOI:10.1007/s00339-015-9123-4); favors ns for 532 nm on reflective surfaces."
      },
      "repetition_rate": {
        "min": 1,
        "max": 200,
        "unit": "kHz",
        "value": 20,
        "description": "Typical 10-100 kHz for cleaning; lower rates reduce heat accumulation on reflective gold. High freq speeds process but risks thermal buildup. Recommended 20 kHz for gold to optimize removal rate vs. safety. Source: Academic literature on pulsed laser cleaning (e.g., Opt. Lasers Eng. 2020, DOI:10.1016/j.optlaseng.2020.106123)."
      },
      "energy_density": {
        "min": 0.1,
        "max": 20,
        "unit": "J/cm²",
        "value": 1,
        "description": "Fluence range below gold's ablation threshold (~1.5-2 J/cm² at 532 nm) for safe contaminant removal. Damage threshold ~2 J/cm²; conservative for high reflectivity. Recommended 1 J/cm² to ablate oxides/dirt without substrate harm. Source: Ablation threshold studies (e.g., J. Appl. Phys. 2012, DOI:10.1063/1.4768264); notes gold's reflectivity requires higher fluence than less reflective metals."
      },
      "spot_size": {
        "min": 0.1,
        "max": 500,
        "unit": "μm",
        "value": 100,
        "description": "Smaller spots (50-100 μm) for fine gold surface prep, larger (200-300 μm) for broad areas. Recommended 100 μm for precise industrial cleaning of gold to control energy delivery. Source: Equipment specifications from Trumpf and Coherent laser systems for micro-cleaning applications."
      },
